author: @SergioLeonardoCornejo

text:
​ @SergioLeonardoCornejo  
>Do you have any idea of how hard it is for me to find authentic Japanese food here in Mexico? It's a nightnare! Rolls with avocado and soy sauce with jalapeño or serrano chili!
Brands always adjust their menu to local tastes. This is why you almost never see not only authentic, but even simple Variations of a knack. Thee idea is that people might "not get it". It was like that in EU. Some guy from Russia decided to open Russian variation of shawarma place in Germany. The business fell flat because it was too different from donor kebab. 
Same with Sushi rolls. Though I am surprised about not be able to find authentic rolls, because they consist of less ingredients than buffed (or debuffed, depending on your taste) ones. Like, just make a position on your menu of regular maki with the ability to add chili and jalapeno for extra price. So I can only assume it is the same thing with "Tako bell". Localized to Burgerland taste. I doubt that sushi places around you didn't do their market research before making the menu.
author: @ljuc

text: @SergioLeonardoCornejo  You have my sympathy... Mountain Dew is pretty great. I did used to drink it when I got Taco Bell. I drink it on occasion when I'm not eating Taco Bell
author: @NeoShot

text:
@ljuc  that's an unfortunate reality.
I do like the real thing, and even though the avocado is not a big issue, the chili pepper part and the tequila part are because I don't like those tastes.
Even when consuming local cuisine I always ask the waiter to serve it without chili peppers or hot sauces.
My taste is unfit for the place I spawned at.
But it wouldn't be an issue beyond the personal level if I didn't see the people upset at Taco Bell's American application of Mexican food doing the same to Japanese, American, and even Italian cuisine.
My own father, who I often clash with ideologically, gets offended by Taco Bell, but will put chipotle to spaghetti or macaroni and cheese, make sushi rolls with cream cheese and avocado, puts hit sauce and jalapeño in burgers and hot dogs, and pollutes soy sauce with tequila.
His excuse is "It makes things tastier." But that is no excuse if one detests Taco Bell.
Otherwise I wouldn't mind that much.

Nah, they knew exactly what they were doing. I do marketing research Pepsi & many huge companies are [finally] starting to embrace YouTube (and Twitch!) more than just 30s-2min ad space in videos with paid promos. You'll start seeing it much more soon. Any paid promo from a huge company is an easy 100k+ payout and they'll gladly pay it. TV watch time is on a downwards trend and ads campaigns can cost millions, so 50k-500k USD (depending on audience size, and time 15m/30m/1hr) is highly worth to any YouTuber, it's a lot of saved money. This was obvious planned before the ad campaign anyways, which is why she was in it.

Just some insight, no clue why I'm talking about work outside of work though.
